{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AumBzrH8v5kZ2hA3cCuzFv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the credentials:\n- Username: admin\n- Password: adminpass\n\nAlso, `loopback_users.guest = false` is set in rabbitmq.conf, which means the `guest` user can be accessed from non-loopback. But there's an `admin` user with password `adminpass`.\n\nLet me verify management API works:\n- `rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless:15672` with admin/adminpass\n\nNow let me plan the solution:\n\n**Approach: Add a `kbudde/rabbitmq-exporter` sidecar to each RabbitMQ pod via StatefulSet modification.**\nI'll use the `kbudde/rabbitmq-exporter:v0.29.0` image which connects to the management API and exposes the `rabbitmq_up` metric. The sidecar will be configured to hit the local management API on port 15672 with the admin credentials, and expose metrics on port 9419. Then I'll update Prometheus to scrape that port from each RabbitMQ pod. Adding the sidecar will trigger a pod recreation, but that's acceptable. I'm realizing the exporter only exposes a single `rabbitmq_up` metric for the management API connection, not per-node metrics. To get three separate samples, I'd need to run three independent exporter instances, each pointing to a different RabbitMQ pod's management API endpoint.\n\nWriting Prometheus config...\n\nBut I'm realizing this approach is getting complex with six Kubernetes resources. Let me step back—maybe the simplest way to get three `rabbitmq_up` samples is to leverage Prometheus's built-in `up` metric, which it automatically generates when successfully scraping a target.\n\nThe challenge is that `up` is a synthetic metric Prometheus creates, so I can't directly rename it through metric relabeling. However, I can create a recording rule that transforms `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` into `rabbitmq_up`, which would give me exactly three samples—one for each RabbitMQ instance.\n\nTo implement this, I need to add the recording rule to Prometheus's configuration. The cleanest approach is to create a separate ConfigMap with the rule file and mount it alongside the main Prometheus config, then reference it in the `rule_files` section.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":205,"cache_read_input_tokens":47552,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":205},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5e1168d4-40ee-46f4-961c-d678fe4ab44e","uuid":"625c8124-142a-48fa-8ecd-7a0d2ff77de6","request_id":"req_011CcMRymWZX4gz2dK8Qh7Eh"}
